ceptions of the organisation, visualisation, and reliability of knowledge. Andrea van Leerdam uncovers the assumptions and intentions of book producers to which images testify, and shows how actual readers engaged with these illustrated books. Drawing on insights from the field of information design studies, she scrutinises the books' material characteristics, including their lay-outs and traces of use, to shed light on the habits and interests of early modern readers. She situates these works in a culture where medicine and astrology were closely interwoven in daily life and where both book producers and readers were exploring the potential of images.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aCultural Studies. 4aDutch and The Netherlands. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aMedia Studies. 7aDESIGN / Book.2bisacsh  ahistory of books, woodcuts, early modern prints, history of knowledge, history of reading.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102374840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048560264?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048560264zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048560264/original  a978-3-11-102374-8 Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA